AUTHORIZATIONS OF APPROPRIATIONS FOR UNITED STATES CUSTOMS SERVICE AND IMMIGRATION AND NATURALIZATION SERVICE. Authorized appropriations for the United States Customs Service to enhance border investigative resources, anticorruption efforts, combat drug smuggling and money-laundering, process cargo, reduce traffic waiting times, and open all primary lanes during peak hours at certain ports on the Southwest and Northern borders. Authorized appropriations for the United States Customs Service include funding for salaries, expenses, and equipment to reduce traffic waiting times and enhance enforcement and inspection resources on the Southwest land border. Specifically, $161,248,584 is allocated for fiscal year 1999, $185,751,328 for fiscal year 2000, and additional sums as necessary in subsequent fiscal years. Authorized appropriations for the United States Customs Service include funding to enhance enforcement and inspection resources on the Southwest land border, combat corruption, drug smuggling, and money-laundering, process cargo, and reduce traffic waiting times. Funding amounts are $161,248,584 for fiscal year 1999, $185,751,328 for fiscal year 2000, and additional sums as needed in subsequent years. The Immigration and Naturalization Service is authorized to receive $113,604,000 for fiscal year 1999 to enhance investigative resources for anticorruption efforts, combat drug smuggling and money-laundering, process cargo, reduce traffic waiting times, and open all primary lanes during peak hours at major land border ports of entry on the Southwest and Northern land borders of the United States. The Immigration and Naturalization Service is authorized to receive funds for salaries, expenses, and equipment for carrying out border security measures, with specific amounts allocated for fiscal years 1999 and 2000, and additional sums as needed in subsequent years. The Immigration and Naturalization Service is authorized to receive funds for border security measures, with specific amounts allocated for fiscal years 1999 and 2000, and additional sums as needed in subsequent years. For fiscal year 1999, $48,404,000 is designated for acquisition and expenses related to narcotics enforcement and cargo processing technology along the Southwest border. For fiscal year 1999, $48,404,000 is allocated for the United States Customs Service for the implementation of narcotics enforcement and cargo processing technology along the Southwest border. This includes funds for Vehicle and Container Inspection Systems (VACIS), mobile truck x-rays, and fixed-site upgrades. For fiscal year 1999, $48,404,000 is allocated for the United States Customs Service for enforcement and cargo processing technology along the Southwest border, including $6,000,000 for 8 VACIS, $11,000,000 for 5 mobile truck x-rays, $12,000,000 for upgrading 8 fixed-site truck x-rays to 1-MeV, $7,200,000 for 8 1-MeV pallet x-rays, and $1,000,000 for 200 portable contraband detectors. For fiscal year 1999, $48,404,000 is allocated for the United States Customs Service for enforcement and cargo processing technology along the Southwest border. This includes upgrading 8 fixed-site truck x-rays to 1-MeV, $7,200,000 for 8 1-MeV pallet x-rays, $1,000,000 for 200 portable contraband detectors, $600,000 for 50 contraband detection kits, and $500,000 for 25 ultrasonic container inspection units. The current allocations include $600,000 for 50 contraband detection kits, $500,000 for 25 ultrasonic container inspection units, $2,450,000 for 7 automated targeting systems, and $360,000 for 30 rapid tire deflator systems. The funding allocations include $480,000 for 20 Portable Treasury Enforcement Communications System (TECS) terminals, $1,000,000 for 20 remote watch surveillance camera systems, and $2,450,000 for 7 automated targeting systems among other security measures at ports. (J) $480,000 for 20 Portable Treasury Enforcement Communications System (TECS) terminals to be moved among ports as needed;
(K) $1,000,000 for 20 remote watch surveillance camera systems at ports with suspicious activities;
(L) $1,254,000 for 57 weigh-in-motion sensors at ports with high outbound traffic;
