 systems, narcotics detectors, and AM radio stations. Funds allocated for maintenance and support of equipment at border patrol checkpoints, including narcotics detectors. For the maintenance and support of equipment at border patrol checkpoints, including narcotics detectors, funds are allocated annually. This includes $4,840,400 for equipment and personnel training, estimated at 10% of the equipment cost, and $1,509,000 specifically for the Immigration and Naturalization Service. The Immigration and Naturalization Service is allocated $1,509,000 annually for equipment maintenance and personnel training. The Commissioner of Customs may use the funds for equipment other than specified in the section. The Commissioner of Customs can use allocated funds for equipment other than specified in the section if the alternative equipment is technologically superior and achieves the same results at a cost that is the same or less. The Commissioner of Customs can reallocate funds for equipment that is technologically superior and achieves the same results at a cost that is the same or less than the specified equipment in the section. The Commissioner of Customs has the authority to reallocate funds for equipment specified in subsection (b)(1) if it can be obtained at a lower cost than the authorized equipment. Additionally, the Attorney General is responsible for the amounts and equipment specified in subsection (b)(2). The Attorney General has authority to allocate funds for equipment specified in subsection (b)(1) not exceeding 10 percent of the specified amounts in subsection (b)(1)(A) through (R). The same authority is granted to the Attorney General for amounts and equipment specified in subsection (b)(2) as the Commissioner of Customs. The Attorney General has the same authority as the Commissioner of Customs for allocating funds for equipment specified in subsection (b)(1) and (b)(2). $112,844,584 in fiscal year 1999 and $180,910,928 for fiscal year 2000 will be allocated for increasing inspectors and special agents on the Southwest border. In fiscal years 1999 and 2000, $112,844,584 and $180,910,928 respectively will be allocated for increasing inspectors and special agents on the Southwest and Northern borders to enhance investigative resources and open all primary lanes during peak hours. Additionally, there will be a net increase of inspectors and canine enforcement officers for large cargo. In order to enhance investigative resources and reduce waiting times on the Southwest border, there will be a net increase of 285 inspectors and canine enforcement officers at large cargo facilities. Additionally, there will be a net increase of 360 special agents and 40 intelligence analysts distributed among offices with jurisdiction. To reduce waiting times on the Southwest border, there will be an increase in resources for processing cargo and screening, including rail cargo. This includes adding 360 special agents, 40 intelligence analysts, and additional resources for offices targeting drug smuggling and money-laundering organizations. Additionally, there will be a net increase of 50 positions for intensified efforts against drug distribution and transportation centers. The curr_chunk discusses the allocation of resources to offices targeting drug smuggling and money-laundering organizations, an increase in positions for the Office of Internal Affairs for anticorruption efforts, and the costs associated with hiring additional personnel. The curr_chunk allocates funds for enhancing investigative resources for anticorruption efforts, including hiring additional personnel for border inspections. The curr_chunk allocates funds for increasing border inspectors and canine enforcement officers, as well as acquiring canine enforcement vehicles for border patrol checkpoints. The curr_chunk allocates resources to increase border patrol lanes, inspectors, canine enforcement officers, vehicles, and intelligence analysts to enhance border security. The curr_chunk allocates additional resources for intelligence analysts and positions to intensify efforts against drug smuggling and money-laundering organizations at the Southwest land border of the United States. The curr_chunk allocates additional resources to patrol sectors with jurisdiction over drug distribution centers, increase positions in the Office of the Inspector General for anticorruption efforts, and cover costs of personnel hired under this section.
